    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-14T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-14T19:00:00-05:00" n="189"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d189">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">865.01/12–1444</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_WJG1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-14T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >December 14, 1944—8 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I want you to know of the reply which <persName corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName>
                    made to me to the personal message which you delivered to him for me, outlined
                    in 10226 of December 6.<note n="1" xml:id="d189fn1">Not printed as such; but for
                        the message of <persName corresp="#p_SERJ1">Stettinius</persName> to
                            <persName corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName> of December 6, see <hi
                            rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_272">p. 272</ref>.</note> In
                    essence, his message thanked me for mine which he termed helpful and
                    understanding. He added that he wished keenly for us to work closely
                    together.</p>
                <pb facs="0361" n="275" xml:id="pg_275"/>
                <p>For your background on this matter, you should know that our statement<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d189fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_266">pp. 266</ref>–<ref
                            target="#pg_267">267</ref>.</note> was issued as a result of
                    considerable pressure on us from our domestic press and that generally speaking,
                    it was received very well in this country by the press and also by the Congress.
                    In conversations with us, the British representatives here admit that they
                    should have consulted us before taking the Italian action, but they blame us in
                    turn for not consulting them before we issued the statement. We would not have
                    issued a public statement had not <persName corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName>’s
                    public declaration on the floor of the House compelled us immediately to
                    disassociate ourselves with that policy publicly.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SERJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
